						<div class="postbody">Here comes the SFC-Box OSD charset.<br />Mark has got hold of a video grabber which gives pretty much perfect screenshots of the charset:<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<a href="./download/file.php?id=443&amp;sid=2c7b19949fad8aae6e2422a708bd7660&amp;mode=view"><img src="./download/file.php?id=443&amp;t=1&amp;sid=2c7b19949fad8aae6e2422a708bd7660" alt="MB90082_screenshot.png" /></a><br />
			<span class="gensmall">MB90082_screenshot.png [ 380.49 KiB | Viewed 15840 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br />Here's the same picture with a red pixel grid:<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<a href="./download/file.php?id=444&amp;sid=2c7b19949fad8aae6e2422a708bd7660&amp;mode=view"><img src="./download/file.php?id=444&amp;t=1&amp;sid=2c7b19949fad8aae6e2422a708bd7660" alt="MB90082_gridded.png" /></a><br />
			<span class="gensmall">MB90082_gridded.png [ 486.01 KiB | Viewed 15840 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div><br />For extracting the &quot;raw&quot; pixels, I've been writing a tool that computes the average pixel color (within the above grid). If it's a clearly black or clearly white pixel then it's takes as is. If it's an unclear &quot;gray&quot; pixel, then the tool is examining the left and right pixels, and adjusts the intensity of the middle pixel to the opposite of the intensity of those left/right pixels, and does then retry to identify the adjusted pixel. The result looks like so:<br /><div class="attachtitle">Attachment:</div><div class="attachcontent">
			<img src="./download/file.php?id=445&amp;sid=2c7b19949fad8aae6e2422a708bd7660" alt="MB90082_pixelized.gif" /><br />
			<span class="gensmall">MB90082_pixelized.gif [ 6.6 KiB | Viewed 15840 times ]</span>
		

		<br />
	</div></div>

